bully
Homonym Number:  5
Word Class: noun
Sense Number:
Definition:a certain tip; the dinkum oil (on a horse) (prob f. <i>bully</i> aj `first rate', i.e. <i>the bully gen</i>, with an ironical play on <i>bull-shit</i>).
Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Domain: [none]
Region: [none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: ca1950 (prob earlier, even 1930s) Auckland (V. O'Sullivan) e.g. I've got the bully on X for Epsom on Saturday. I got the bully straight from the horse's mouth.
Citations
Date:  0/0/1937
Source:  Dictionary of Slang
Author:  PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page:  105
Edition:
Quote:  <i>Bully.</i> adj. First-rate, `champion', splendid: Canada, Aust and NZ, from ca1860, ex US ... .us; <i>Ex the late 17-18C. S.E.</i> bully, <i>worthy, admirable, applied only to persons. </i>
